---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="The KV Cache Stores Past Attention State">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L29" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What does the KV cache store?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        During attention, each token's query (Q) needs to interact with the keys (K) and values (V) of all previous tokens. Without caching, every decode step would recompute K and V for every token from scratch — repeating all the work from every prior step.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">KV cache</strong> stores the K and V projections that have already been computed. When a new token arrives during decode, the model only computes K and V for that one new token and appends them to the cache. The query then attends to the full cached sequence.
      </p>
      <p>
        This avoids quadratic recomputation — but it costs memory. The cache stores one K vector and one V vector per token, per layer, per KV head. (In GQA/MQA models, there are fewer KV heads than query heads — which is one reason those variants exist.) For a dense model with 32 layers, 32 KV heads, d_head=128, and float16, the cache is 2 &times; 32 &times; 32 &times; 128 &times; 2 bytes = <strong>512 KB per token</strong>. A 4,096-token context uses about 2 GB of KV cache alone.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Generating tokens after a 3-token prompt, showing cache growth:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">prefill:</span> process [A, B, C] &rarr; <span style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">cache = [K,V for A, B, C]</span>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">decode step 1:</span> process [D] &rarr; <span style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">cache = [K,V for A, B, C, D]</span>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">decode step 2:</span> process [E] &rarr; <span style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">cache = [K,V for A, B, C, D, E]</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          The cache grows by one entry per token generated. Each entry is (K, V) for every layer and KV head.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">K cache per layer per KV head: [n_past, d_head]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">V cache per layer per KV head: [n_past, d_head]</div>
        <div style="margin-top: var(--space-2);">Total cache: 2 &times; n_layers &times; n_kv_heads &times; n_past &times; d_head &times; sizeof(element)</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">Memory grows linearly with n_past. Longer sequences = more cache memory.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <p>Without the cache, decode step t would recompute K for all t tokens:</p>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">// Without cache (wasteful):</div>
        <div>K = X_[1:t] &middot; W_K &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">// recompute K for ALL tokens every step</span></div>
        <div style="margin-top: var(--space-3); color: var(--ink-tertiary);">// With cache (actual):</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">k_new = x_t &middot; W_K &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">// compute K for new token only</span></div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-kvcache);">K = concat(K_cached, k_new) &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">// append to cache</span></div>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary);">
        The same applies to V. This turns O(t&sup2;) recomputation into O(t) append-and-read.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Why Cache and Not Recompute?</div>
      <p>
        Without the KV cache, generating the t-th token would require rerunning the K and V projections for all t tokens.
        Over a 100-token generation, this means computing K/V for: 1 + 2 + 3 + ... + 100 = 5,050 token-projection operations.
        With the cache, you compute K/V for exactly 100 tokens total (each once, then cached). The cache trades memory for
        a ~50&times; reduction in redundant compute at this sequence length — and the savings grow linearly with generation length.
      </p>
      <p>
        The tradeoff is clear: the cache uses memory that scales with context length, but it avoids re-doing work that
        grows <em>quadratically</em> without it. For any non-trivial generation length, caching wins overwhelmingly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Cache Management: Pre-allocation and Eviction</div>
      <p>
        In practice, the KV cache is <strong>pre-allocated</strong> for the maximum context length when the inference
        context is created. A model configured with n_ctx = 8192 allocates cache for 8192 tokens upfront, even if
        the first prompt is only 100 tokens. This avoids expensive reallocation during generation but means unused
        cache slots consume memory.
      </p>
      <p>
        For SWA layers, entries older than the window size can be <strong>evicted</strong> — their slots are reused for
        new tokens. For full-attention layers, entries must be retained for the full context. Real implementations
        track which slots are active and which can be reclaimed.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, the KV cache is allocated once when the context is created. During each decode step, new K and V entries are written into the cache at the current position. The cache memory is pre-allocated for the full context length, even if only a fraction is used so far. When a request finishes, its cache slots are freed for the next request.
        </p>
        <div class="file-path">src/llama-kv-cache.cpp &mdash; KV cache allocation and update</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          The KV cache is often the dominant memory consumer during inference — larger than the memory needed for activations. Quantizing the cache (e.g., to Q8 or Q4) reduces its footprint but introduces approximation. Techniques like GQA (grouped-query attention) reduce cache size by sharing K/V across head groups, which is why many modern models use it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L29"
        gateStrength="hard"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L29-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'A model has 32 layers, 8 KV heads per layer, and d_head = 128. A user sends a 1,000-token prompt. Roughly how many float values does the KV cache hold after prefill?',
            tag: 'math',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: '1,000 × 32 × 8 × 128 × 2 ≈ 65.5M (one K + one V per head per layer per token)', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'b', text: '1,000 × 32 × 128 ≈ 4.1M (one vector per layer per token)', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: '32 × 8 × 128 × 2 ≈ 65K (cache size is independent of token count)', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'Each token adds one K and one V vector (both of size d_head) per KV head per layer. Total: n_tokens × n_layers × n_kv_heads × d_head × 2 = 1000 × 32 × 8 × 128 × 2 = 65,536,000 values. The cache grows linearly with token count — this is why long contexts are expensive.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L29-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'If you switch from full multi-head attention (32 KV heads) to GQA with 8 KV heads, what happens to the KV cache size?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'It becomes 4× smaller (8/32 = 1/4)', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'b', text: 'It stays the same because Q still has 32 heads', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: 'It doubles because the shared heads need more capacity', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The KV cache stores entries per KV head, not per Q head. Reducing KV heads from 32 to 8 reduces cache size by 4×. Q heads are not cached — only K and V are. This is the main inference motivation for GQA.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
